ar’.","Czech: from a short form of the old personal name   Strachota  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Slovenian and Croatian   Strah  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Strah","meanings":["Slovenian and Croatian: nickname from <i>strah</i> ‘fear’, applied either to an easily frightened or to a fearful person.","Americanized form of Czech and Polish   Strach  , a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Strachota","meanings":["Czech and Polish: from the old personal name <i>Strachota</i>, derived from <i>strach</i> ‘fear’. In some cases it was an erroneous translation of the Greek personal name <i>Methodios</i> (thought to be derived from Latin <i>metus</i> ‘fear’ instead of Greek <i>methodos</i> ‘pursuit, method’), borne by St. Methodius (826–869), a missionary who, together with his brother Cyril, brought Christianity to the Slavs."]}]},{"name":"Christina","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Simplified form of Latin <i>Christiana</i>, feminine form of <i>Christianus</i> (  see  Christian  ), or a Latinized form of Middle English <i>Christin</i> ‘Christian’ (Old English <i>christen</i>, from Latin)."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":0,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Christina Strech was born in 1382, in Ruscombe, Berkshire, England as the daughter of William Stretch of Rushcombe, Berkshire. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Sir William Norreys Esq of  Ockwells. She died in 1425, in Bray Hundred, Berkshire, England, at the age 